Firstly, thanks for refering to my solution, in advance :)

 **Valley Peak approach :** 
We buy the stock on the day with least local rate and sell it when we find a peak that is raise in prices again. i.e; we just need to find the next greater element and subtract it from the current element so that the difference keeps increasing and so does the profit.
If the sequence is decreasing sequence then, no profit can be made because no matter on which day we buy the stock, we would have to sell it incurring a loss. So then we don't buy and make '0' profit rather than negative. 
We can just understand which day we buy and sell the stock, by simply using a peak Valley Diagram.

For instance, 
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/8a071173-ac5b-4bda-97a9-74da3637398d_1636509428.7270691.png)
* Here, the first valley is seen on day-2, we buy the stock on day2 and sell when the prices raise the next day, i.e on day-3 - Profit+=A
* Then again, we buy on the day the next valley is seen on day-4, so we buy on day-4 and sell on the day, the next peak is seen i.e; on day-5 - Profit+=B
Thus, the max-profit we can make with this sequence of stock-rates is A+B.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/47631773-0c33-4080-ac31-1e8942f64b2b_1636509698.8262544.png) In this graph, we see the first valley on day-3, we buy on day-3, sell on day-4. 
Then again, the price on day-5 is less than that on day-4, So we buy again on day-4 and sell on day-5. 
Similarly, we buy on day-5 again and sell on day-6.
The Valley-Peak graph is known in advance to us. So, we can see the future prices and make decision accordingly.

**Time and Space Complexity**
* Time Complexity - O(n) - We traverse through the array of stock-rates only once
* Auxiliary Space - O(1)

