solutions.content:
***Recursive Approach :***
The question says we can buy and sell as many stocks we want, on a condition that we have to sell after each buy.

***We have 2 choices at each index:***
If we haven't bought any stock then we have to buy:
```
We can either buy or leave that stock i.e. ans = max ( buy, not-buy);
```
If we have to sell a stock we can,
```
ans = max (sell, not-sell);
```

**Recursion Tree**
```
Let curr be final sum

        [7,1,5,3,6,4]
		  /        \
    	Buy         Not Buy
     (Curr=-7)     (Curr=0)
	 /       \ 
 Sell	   Not Sell 
Curr=-6     Curr=-7

II'ly the recursion tree will grow
```

Conditions :- We will have a variable for index and buy,
```
if( buy) ans = max (-nums[i] + solve ( for sell), solve ( forbuy));
if( !buy) ans = max (nums[i] + solve (for buy), solve (sell)); 
```

```
class Solution {
public:

    int solve(vector<int>&nums,int i,bool buy){   

        if(i>=nums.size()) return 0;
        if(buy){   // we can buy at curr index or not buy   
            return dp[i][buy]=max(-nums[i]+solve(nums,i+1,!buy),solve(nums,i+1,buy));  
        }
        else{     //we can sell at curr index or not sell
            return dp[i][buy]=max(nums[i]+solve(nums,i+1,!buy),solve(nums,i+1,buy));  
        }
    }

    int maxProfit(vector<int>& prices) {
        int n=prices.size();
        if(n<2) return 0;
        return solve(prices,0,true); 
    }
};
```

**Complxeity**
```
Time : O(2^N) // we have two choices at n steps
Space : O(2^N)
```

***MEMOIZATION***
*We can observe repeated number of same recursive calls in this questions, 
We can observe two variables in our recursion calls, so we will use memoization with the help of 2-D matrix*

```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>>dp;

    int solve(vector<int>&nums,int i,bool buy){   

        if(i>=nums.size()) return 0;
        if(dp[i][buy]!=-1) return dp[i][buy];
        if(buy){      
            return dp[i][buy]=max(-nums[i]+solve(nums,i+1,!buy),solve(nums,i+1,buy));  
        }
        else{
            return dp[i][buy]=max(nums[i]+solve(nums,i+1,!buy),solve(nums,i+1,buy));  
        }
    }

    int maxProfit(vector<int>& prices) {
        int n=prices.size();
        if(n<2) return 0;
        dp.resize(n+1,vector<int>(2,-1));
        return solve(prices,0,true); 
    }
};
```

**Complxeity**
```
Time : O(N)
Space : O(N)
```

***Peak Valley Solution (Greedy)***
Another intelligent solution is greedy solution which will solve this question in `O(n) time and O(1) space`
As we know that we can only buy or sell at a certain index (As it is saying that be maximum productive or profitable in current time, don't care about future)

We can vizualize the current stock prices in the form of a graph

```
[7,1,5,3,6,4]

7
\               6
 \       5     /\
  \     / \   /  \
   \   /   \ /    4
    \ /     3
	 1
```
As we can see, if we calculate the maximum profit for every local maxima we observe we can have the maximum profit, eg : `[1->5] [3->6]`
So, in this approach we have simply calculated profit at every local maixima we observe

```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxProfit(vector<int>& nums) {
        int ans=0;
        for(int i=1;i<nums.size();i++){
            if(nums[i]>nums[i-1]){
                ans+=nums[i]-nums[i-1];
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```
**Complxeity**
```
Time : O(N)
Space : O(1)
```

