solutions.content:
The best way to solve any question related to buy and sell stock is by making state machines.
It is very intuitive to draw the state machine for this question.
There are three things we need to do
1) Buy
2) Hold
3) Sell

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/7d650a21-13c8-44d6-b88d-6f591b963c49_1657615804.1454897.png)

We have two states x and y.
In state x we have to decide if we want to buy a stock or do nothing.
In state y we have to decide if we want to sell a stock or do nothing.
To move from state x to y we have to buy a stock, similarly from y to x we have to sell the stock.

Our task is to maximize the profit hence in each state we take decision by looking at maximum profit.
To write the state equation we look at the incoming edges on a given state.

The state equations are:
**x[i] = max( x[i-1] , y[i-1] + prices[i])
y[i]= max( y[i-1] , x[i-1] - prices[i])**

**Note: Here we are deciding at current price we need to buy or sell or hold the stock, thats why we have to take prices[i] and not prices[i-1].**

 C++ code with O(n) space:
 ```
 int maxProfit(vector<int>& prices) {
		int n=prices.size();
        vector<int> x(n,0),y(n);
		// initially we dont have anything, so moving to state y requires prices[0]
        y[0]=-prices[0];
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++)
        {
            x[i]=max(x[i-1],y[i-1]+prices[i]);
            y[i]=max(x[i-1]-prices[i],y[i-1]); 

        }
        return max(x[n-1],y[n-1]);
		}
```

And with little tweaking the space is optimized to O(1):
```
int maxProfit(vector<int>& prices) {
		int y=-prices[0];
        int x=0,last_x=0;
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++)
        {
            x=max(last_x,y+prices[i]);
            y=max(last_x-prices[i],y);
            last_x=x;
        }

        return max(x,y);
		}
```

