solutions.content:
I approached this problem with a stock market perspective - what would you do if you were actually there, with a crystal ball.

So I decided to go hunting for local minima (because that is how you properly do the plural form of Latin *-um* words!) and local maxima, defined as numbers who are respectively lower or higher than their neighbours.

I don't even need to store the maxima, since every time I catch them, I can just increase my accumulator variable `res`  by a `n - lMin` amount and move on.

Once I parsed the whole vector, I return `res`.

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int maxProfit(vector<int>& prices) {
        int lMin = prices[0], res = 0, lastValue = prices.size() - 1, n;
        for (int i = 0; i < prices.size(); i++) {
            n = prices[i];
            // checking if the value is a local min
            if ((!i || prices[i - 1] > n) && (i == lastValue || n <= prices[i + 1])) {
                lMin = n;
            }
            // checking if the value is a local max
            if ((!i || prices[i - 1] < n) && (i == lastValue || n >= prices[i + 1])) {
                res += n - lMin;
                lMin = n;
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

Then I realised that unlike the real stock market, there are no transactions costs here, so I might as well think of selling and buying every single time the previous value suggest so and I got this more efficient solution:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int maxProfit(vector<int>& prices) {
        int prev = prices[0], res = 0;
        for (int curr: prices) {
            if (prev < curr) res += curr - prev;
            prev = curr;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

I guess there are times in which too much domain knowledge is more of a burden than an asset.

Discussion of the most general case of `k` different sales [here](https://leetcode.com/problems/best-time-to-buy-and-sell-stock-iv/discuss/900061/).

