# Intuition
Looking at the examples, it looks like making the sale just before the prices drops the first time since the buy day, ignoring there might be a higher price in the future and then repeat from the new, lower price.
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
1. three vars to keep track of buy price (min), highest price including buy day (max), and the total profit (sum).
2. Store day one prices in min and max
3. Loop through the prices. 
3.1 if the price is higher than max, update max. 
3.2 if the price is lower than max: 1) add diff(max-min) to sum. 2) update max and min with new day price. 
4. When the loop finishes, add diff(max-min) to sum in case the last day was not a sell. 
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n) where n is size of the array
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1) since only three variables is needed. 
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public int MaxProfit(int[] prices) 
    {
        if(prices.Length < 2) {return 0;}
        int min = prices[0];
        int max = prices[0];
        int sum = 0;
        for(int i = 1; i < prices.Length; i++)
        {
            if(prices[i] > max)
            {
                max = prices[i];
                continue;
            }
            if(prices[i] < max)
            {
                sum += max - min;
                min = prices[i];
                max = prices[i];
            }
        }
        sum+= max - min;

        return sum;
    }
}
```

