solutions.content:
My logic is when we are in a current node... We can see we have 2 cases for SUBTREE heights:
A. if both lh(left subtree height)  == rh(right subtree height)
B. lh > rh 

for A we go to the right as we can observe that we have inequality on the RIGHT
and for B we go the the left as we observe we can have inequality on the LEFT 

ONLY base case is if rh == 0 then there are two cases (SEE CODE :)

The trick part is to take care on how many nodes we have covered till now.. We can use "CUR":
and can use the property that left  = (2xCUR) and right = (2xCUR + 1)... 

and rest is as it is..

```
int ans;
class Solution {
    int height(TreeNode *root){
        if(root == NULL) return 0;
        int h = 1;
        int lh = height(root->left), rh = height(root->right);
        h += max(lh, rh);
        return h;
    }
public:
    int countNodes(TreeNode* root, int cur = 1) {
        ans = 0;
        if(root == NULL) return 0;
        int lh = height(root->left), rh = height(root->right);
        if(rh == 0)
            if(root->left != NULL) ans = cur*2;
            else ans = cur;
        else
            if(lh == rh) countNodes(root->right, cur*2 + 1);
            else countNodes(root->left, cur*2);

        return ans;
    }
};
```


