solutions.content:
First we get the height of the tree and compute the sum, assuming that it is a complete tree.
The idea is finding the depth of leftest branch because it would be the deepest one of the subtree.
Each time compare the tree height between the leftest branch of left child and leftest branch of right child.
If they are equal, then the gap (the place makes tree not complete) lies in right child, and we move to there.
If they are not equal, then the gap lies in left child or in between, and we have to subtract the missing node in right child.
This gives us Time Complexity of sum_(h = 1)^(h = log(n)) (log(h)).
So we find that the integral of log(x) for x from 1 to x is xlog(x).
For this problem, it's xlog(x) when x = log(n), which is log(n)log(log(n)).
```
class Solution {
private:
    int getLeftDepth(TreeNode* root) {
        if (root == NULL) return 0;
        return getLeftDepth(root->left) + 1;
    }
public:
    int countNodes(TreeNode* root) {
        if (root == NULL) return 0;
        int h = getLeftDepth(root);
        TreeNode* curr = root;
        int lh = h, rh = h, nextH = h;
        int ans = (1 << h) - 1;
        while (curr->left != NULL) {
            nextH--;
            lh = getLeftDepth(curr->left);
            rh = getLeftDepth(curr->right);
            if (rh < lh) {
                ans -= (1 << rh);
                curr = curr->left;
            }
            else
                curr = curr->right;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

