solutions.content:
### Idea
- Total number of nodes = total number of nodes not in the last level + nodes in the last level
- total number of nodes not in the last level = 2^h - 1
- total number of nodes in the last level can be found using binary search
- `exist` is the core of the algorithm. Index nodes starting with 1, the leftmost node of level i (root is at level 0) is indexed 2^i. For node x, each 1 in the binary digit means going right, each 0 means going left (ignore the leftmost 1). Example: 4 means root->left->left, 3 means root->right.

```C++
class Solution {
    int getHeight(TreeNode *node) {
        int height = 0;
        while (node && node->left) {
            ++height;
            node = node->left;
        }
        return height;
    }

    bool exist(TreeNode* node, int idx, int h) {
        int mask = (1 << h) >> 1; // Use (1 << h) >> 1 to replace 1 << (h-1). Consider h = 0.
        while (mask) {
            node = (mask & idx) ? node->right : node->left;
            mask >>= 1;

            if (!node) {
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }

public:
    int countNodes(TreeNode* root) {
        if (!root) return 0;
        int h = getHeight(root);
        int start = 1 << h, end = (start << 1);
        while (start < end) {
            int mid = (start + end) >> 1;
            if (exist(root, mid, h)) start = mid+1;
            else end = mid;
        }
        return (1 << h)-1 + (start - (1<<h));
    }
};
```

### Implementation issue
- Use `(1 << h) >> 1` instead of `1 << (h-1)`. Edge case: h = 0.
- For the binary search, `end` is set to be `(start<<1)` instead of `(start << 1) -1` at the beginning. We are finding the leftmost index that does NOT exist. 


Reference:
https://leetcode-cn.com/problems/count-complete-tree-nodes/solution/wan-quan-er-cha-shu-de-jie-dian-ge-shu-by-leetco-2/1056014

