![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/dfdfb971-6976-4568-af15-7b0139b69610_1627492207.6966398.png)

We First consider the maximum possible and minimum possible nodes from the depth of the tree.
Then we try to narrow down the range of possible nodes by searching in the tree. As you can see the in every subtree we take left or right based on whether the node we are searching is in the left subtree or right subtree.

Let's take an example. (The values mentioned in the diagram are not necessarily node's values. they are just numbered sequentially for understanding). For a height of 4. the minimum = 8. and maximum = 15. Let's say we want to navigate to the 10th node. Currently we are root node which is 1. Then the whole range of the subtree we have is 8 to 15. The middle of this is 8 + (15-8)/2 = 8 + 3 = 11. So we have to take left.. so 1->left => 2. Now the range becomes 8 to 11. Now the subtreeMiddle is 8 + (11 - 8)/2 = 8 + 1 = 9. But out target is 10. so we take right and the range is 10 to 11. Now the subtreeMiddle is 10. so we take left. We have reached the node and it is present. We are now sure that the minimum number of nodes is atleast 10.  So we make minimumNodes = 10 and maximumNodes to 15. Same way we then look for the existence of the node 12 afterwards and minimum becomes 12. now we check for 13 it is also present.  Then range minimizes to [13,14]. Now the node 14 is not present. Hence we reduce maximum = 13. Now minimum and maximum becomes equals and the loop terminates. Thus we have found the number of nodes in the complete binary tree.


Time Complexity : `O(log^2  (N))` [log squared N]
Because we do binary search inside another binary search both of which take logarithmic of N. 

Space Complexity : `O(1)`
We do not use any extra space.


```
/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode() {}
 *     TreeNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     TreeNode(int val, TreeNode left, TreeNode right) {
 *         this.val = val;
 *         this.left = left;
 *         this.right = right;
 *     }
 * }
 */
class Solution {
    public int countNodes(TreeNode root) {
        if (root == null) {// base case
            return 0;
        } else if (root.left == null && root.right == null) {
			return 1;
		}
        int depth = 0;
        TreeNode node = root;
        while (node.left != null) {// compute the depth of the tree
            node = node.left;
            depth++;
        }

        int maximumNodes = 1;

        int temp = depth;
        while (temp-- > 0){
            maximumNodes = (maximumNodes << 1) | 1;//maximum possible nodes in the complete binary tree of this depth
        }

        int minimumNodes = (maximumNodes >> 1 ) + 1;// minimum possible nodes in the complete binary tree of this depth

        int offsetLow = minimumNodes;
        int offsetHigh = maximumNodes;

        while (minimumNodes < maximumNodes) {

            int middle = minimumNodes + (maximumNodes - minimumNodes)/2;

            if (maximumNodes - minimumNodes == 1) {
                middle = maximumNodes;
            }

            int currentDepth = 0;
            node = root;
            int left = offsetLow;
            int right = offsetHigh;
            while (currentDepth < depth) {// search for the existence of the middle node in the tree
                int subTreeMiddle = left + (right - left)/2;
                if (middle <= subTreeMiddle) {
                    node = node.left;
                    right = subTreeMiddle;
                } else {
                    node = node.right;
                    left = subTreeMiddle + 1;
                }
                currentDepth++;
            }

            if (node != null) {
                minimumNodes = middle;
            } else {
                maximumNodes = middle-1;
            }
        }

        return maximumNodes;
    }
}
```

