solutions.content:
The problem can be solved by doing inorder, postorder, preorder and level order traversals, which will have a time complexity of O(n).

However, the follow-up requests for a solution faster than O(n). This solution is approx. - O(logn x logn), as we move through half of branches at a time for each visited node's sub-tree.

The main idea here is to use the Complete binary tree property i.e. all levels are filled except the last one from left to right. 

So, if a sub-tree is fully complete, that means that the left traversal to deepest node will be equal to right traversal of the deepest node. 
Applying the formula- 2^depth - 1, we can find the number of nodes for this sub-tree.

We perform this recursively to find the total number of nodes. A leaf node always has equal left traversal depth and right traversal depth i.e. 1

You can do dry-runs on multiple examples to visualise and understand how it works.

```
class Solution {
    public int countNodes(TreeNode root) {

		// If node is null, we return 0 count
        if(root == null) {
            return 0;
        }

		// We set curr variable to left node or the root of left sub-tree. 
        TreeNode curr = root.left;

		// Including the current node, the initial depth is 1
        int leftDepth = 1; int rightDepth = 1;

		// We traverse deep into the left childs to find the depth along left boundary of the sub-tree
        while(curr != null) {
            leftDepth++;
            curr = curr.left;
        }

		// We reset the curr variable, so that we can find depth along the right child's path
        curr = root.right;

		// We traverse deep into the right childs to find the depth along right boundary of the sub-tree
        while(curr != null) {
            rightDepth++;
            curr = curr.right;
        }

		/* If both leftDepth and rightDepth are the same, then this means the sub-tree is completely filled. 
		    Hence, we return the count via the formula. We no longer need to traverse any further on this sub-tree.*/
        if(leftDepth == rightDepth) {
            return ((int)Math.pow(2, leftDepth)) -1;
        }

		/* If leftDepth and rightDepth are not the same, then there exists a deeper sub-tree which is not completely filled
		   As we recurse further, we will find the subtree which is completely balanced 
		   i.e. every leaf node will have leftDepth and rightDepth equal to 1
		   We add 1 to include the current node's count. */
        return 1 + countNodes(root.left) + countNodes(root.right);
    }
}
```

