solutions.content:
Treat Complete binary tree as a Perfect binary tree and find the first `NULL` node in the last level and then return total number of nodes above last level + number of nodes before first `NULL` in the last level.
If height of the tree is equals to the height of the subtree means last node is NOT `NULL` otherwise `NULL`. So if it is `NULL` we'll recurse for the left subtree else recurse for right subtree. This way we'll find the first `NULL` node in the last level.

Time Complexity: $$O(log^2(n))$$
Space Complexity: $$O(log(n))$$

```
int height(TreeNode* root){
	int h = 0;
	while(root){
        ++h;
        root=root->left;
    } 
	return h;
}

int countNodes(TreeNode* root) {
	int h = height(root);
	if(h==0) return h;
	const int H = h, leafNodes = 1<<(H-1);
	int low = 1, high = leafNodes, mid, temp;
	while(low <= high && root){
		mid = low + ((high-low)>>1);
		temp = height(root->right) + 1;
		if(temp != h) {
			root = root->left;
			high = mid-1;
		}
		else {
			root = root->right;
			low = mid+1;
		} 
		--h;
	}

	if(low > leafNodes) --low;
	return leafNodes - 1 + (low);
}
```

