First find the depth of the left-most node, call it d1 (where depth of root = 0). Then find depth of right-most node, call it d2. Since the tree is complete, d1 == d2 or d1-1 == d2. If d1 == d2, then the total number of nodes will be 2^(d1+1)-1, since the tree is fully populated. On the other hand, if d1-1 == d2, we compute the number of leaves by traversing the tree again up to the last but one level and the parent node to the leaves will check how many child leaves exist. The number of nodes up till the last but one level is 2^(d1)-1. Thus, the total number of nodes will be 2^(d1)-1 + number of leaves. Note that we do not visit the leaf nodes in the second step and so only log(N) nodes are visited. 


		if root == None:
            return 0

        d1 = 0
        n = root
        while n.left is not None:
            n = n.left
            d1 += 1

        d2 = 0
        n = root
        while n.right is not None:
            n = n.right
            d2 += 1

        assert d1 == d2 or d1-1 == d2

        if d1 == d2:
            return 2**(d1+1)-1

        self.leaves = 0

        def trav_tree(n, depth):

            if depth == d2:
                if n.right is not None:
                    self.leaves += 2
                elif n.left is not None and n.right == None:
                    self.leaves += 1

            if depth < d2:
                trav_tree(n.left, depth+1)
                trav_tree(n.right, depth+1)

        trav_tree(root, 0)

        return 2**(d1)-1 + self.leaves

